HOWEVER!<br>
<br>
Players dont assume the risk of running a franchise.  You cant just add up the profit of a successful club and go ok the bulk of this should go to the players.  Thats bull.  A club purchaser assumes huge risk.  in a well formed market a baseball team will sale at a resonable value + how much risk the buyer is willing to assume (ie how rosy does the buyer see the ticket sales).  the buyer willing to see it the rosiest pays the most.  RISK.  Also keep in mind a non saleing owner assumes risk by NOT SALEING.  if a owner doesnt sale when his club has a resonable value to someone else the owner takes the chance that the club wont get into a ticket saleing rut.  RISK.<br>
<br>
Players dont assume that risk.  tickets dont sale; they loose nothing.   They get traded to a team with high ticket sales cause their contract is to expensive for the guy that errantly assumed to much risk.  Yet when thats not true players want a piece of the profit like that risk wasnt a factor.<br>
<br>
